### Description

Since we have to use `foo = input<any>()` instead of `@Input() foo: any;`, there is an edge-case where I am blocked.

I am using a service which allows to dynamically create and inject a component in the body (like ionic controllers, for instance ModalController, AlertController etc...).

Here is a code-like of what I'm currently doing with the traditionnal way :

```ts
@Injectable({
    providedIn: 'root'
})
export abstract class UIController<T extends UIComponent, C extends UIConfig> {
    constructor(
        @Inject(DOCUMENT)
        private readonly document: Document,
        private readonly appRef: ApplicationRef,
    ) {}

    protected instanciate(component: Type<T>, config: UIConfig, instanceFeedFn: (instance: T) => void): T {
        const componentRef: ComponentRef<T> = createComponent(component, {
            environmentInjector: this.appRef.injector,
        });

        componentRef.instance.foo = config.bar; // <<!
        this.appRef.attachView(componentRef.hostView);

        const uiEl = (componentRef.hostView as any).rootNodes[0];
        this.document.body.appendChild(uiEl);

        return componentRef.instance;
    }
}
```

And now, using signals, the line `componentRef.instance.foo = config.bar` does not work anymore.
I cannot do `componentRef.instance.foo.set(config.bar)` nor `componentRef.instance.foo.update(() => config.bar)` as it is not a writableSignal.

I understand why, initially, an input should be read-only, but it is currently really limiting some useful process, implementations and features.

